\section{Musical scales and tuning systems}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Terminology and equal temperament}
\bi

\item An International Conference in London 
in 1939 established
A$_4$ = 440~Hz as the standard reference frequency.
Before that time, A$_4$ was tuned to different
frequencies ranging from 422.5~Hz (Handel) to
444~Hz, depending on composer, orchestra, ...

\item Scale: succession of notes in ascending or
descending order.

\item Different scales correspond to different
divisions of the octave---chromatic (12 intervals),
diatonic (7 intervals), 
pentatonic (5 intervals). 

\i For example, 
a chromatic scale divides the octave into 
12 intervals called {\em semitones} or {\em half-steps}.
In {\em equal temperament} tuning, 
these intervals all have
the same size, corresponding to a frequency ratio of 
%
\be
2^{1/12} = 1.05946
\ee
%
A {\em whole tone} is exactly equal to two semitones.

\i Vincenzo Galilei (father of Galileo Galilei)
and Chu Tsai-Yu (a Chinese scholar) independently
proposed an equal-tempered chromatic scale around 1580.

\i But equal-tempered tuning didn't become popular 
until the 1700's.
``The Well-Tempered Clavier" by Johannes Sebastian Bach 
demonstrated the usefulness of equal-temperament.
Using all 24 major and minor keys, this piece sounded
good only in equal-tempered tuning, and not in the other
tuning systems that we will describe below.

\i A {\em cent} is a frequency interval equal to
1/100 of a semitone in equal temperament.
This corresponds to a frequency ratio of
%
\be
2^{1/1200} = 1.000578
\ee
%

\i The human ear can distinguish frequencies
that differ by about 10 cents, which corresponds to 
a frequency ratio of $2^{10/1200}=1.00579$, 
or about a 0.5\% difference in frequency.
(We will discuss this in more detail in a later
section when we talk about {\em just noticeable
difference} for pitch.)

\i Table~\ref{t:equal-temperament} gives the frequency
ratios for a chromatic scale in equal-temperament tuning.
%
\begin{table}[htbp]
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
\hline
Note & ET freq ratio \\
\hline
C & $2^{0/12}=1.000$ \\
C$^\sharp$/D$^\flat$ & $2^{1/12}=1.059$ \\
D & $2^{2/12}=1.122$ \\
D$^\sharp$/E$^\flat$ & $2^{3/12}=1.189$ \\
E & $2^{4/12}=1.260$ \\
F & $2^{5/12}=1.335$ \\
F$^\sharp$/G$^\flat$ & $2^{6/12}=1.414$ \\
G & $2^{7/12}=1.498$ \\
G$^\sharp$/A$^\flat$ & $2^{8/12}=1.587$ \\
A & $2^{9/12}=1.682$ \\
A$^\sharp$/B$^\flat$ & $2^{10/12}=1.782$ \\
B & $2^{11/12}=1.888$ \\
C$'$ & $2^{12/12}=2.000$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\caption{Notes in a chromatic scale and the 
corresponding equal-temperament frequency ratios.}
\label{t:equal-temperament}
\end{center}
\end{table}

\i Figure~\ref{f:chromatic-scale-keyboard} shows the
corresponding notes on a piano keyboard.
%
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\begin{center}
