\subsection{Diatonic scales}
\bi

\i A diatonic scale divides the octave into 
7 intervals consisting of both tones and semitones.
The order of tones and semitones 
defines the {\em major} interval order, 
{\em minor} interval order, and various 
{\em modes} (e.g., Dorian, Phrygian, Lydian, ...)
as shown in Figure~\ref{f:diatonic-interval-order}.
%
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.6\textwidth]{modes}
%\includegraphics[width=.6\textwidth]{diatonic-interval-order}
\caption{Interval orders for a diatonic scale:
major, minor, and various modes.}
\label{f:diatonic-interval-order}
\end{center}
\end{figure}
%

\i The diatonic major interval order is 
T-T-S-T-T-T-S (2-2-1-2-2-2-1).
This is the standard
%
\be
{\rm do-re-mi-fa-sol-la-ti-do}
\nonumber
\ee
%
interval order.

\i The diatonic minor interval order is
T-S-T-T-S-T-T (2-1-2-2-1-2-2).

