\subsection{Major and minor key signatures}
\bi

\i Major and minor key signatures can be read off a 
circle-of-fifths diagram if we draw appropriate `wedges'
on the diagram as shown in Figure~\ref{f:major-minor-keys}.
(The diagram for major key scales is shown on the left;
the diagram for minor key scales is shown on the right.)
Simply `dial the wedge' so that that the numeral I points
to the tonic.  
Subsequent keys in the scale are given by numerals II, III, ...
%
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{major-keys} &
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{minor-keys} 
\end{tabular}
\caption{Diagrams for reading off major and minor key scales
(left panel and right panel, respectively).
`Dial the wedge' so that the numeral I points to the tonic.}
\label{f:major-minor-keys}
\end{center}
\end{figure}
%

\i For example, the C-major and C-minor diatonic scales are:
\be
{\rm C-D-E-F-G-A-B}
\nonumber
\ee
% 
and
%
\be
{\rm C-D-E}^\flat{\rm -F-G-G}^\sharp{\rm -A}^\sharp
\nonumber
\ee

\i The notes in the G-major scale are the same as for C-major 
except for F$^\sharp$:
%
\be
{\rm G-A-B-C-D-E-F}^\sharp
\nonumber
\ee
% 

\i The notes in the F-major scale are the same as for C-major 
except for B$^\flat$:
%
\be
{\rm F-G-A-B}^\flat{\rm -C-D-E}
\nonumber
\ee
% 

\i In general, moving clockwise around the circle of fifths
increases the number of sharps in the key signature by one.
Moving counter-clockwise around the circle of fifths increases
the number of flats in the key signature by one.

\i Note that the A-minor scale is
%
\be
{\rm A-B-C-D-E-F-G}
\nonumber
\ee
% 
so the notes are {\em exactly} the same as for C-major.
But because the tonic (and tonal interval order) are 
different for these two scales, they sound differently.

