\subsection{Mean-tone temperament}
\bi

\i Mean-tone temperament (or {\em quarter-comma mean-tone 
temperament}) is a tuning system that tries to correct the
problem with Pythagorean major thirds by flattening them with 
the syntonic comma $\delta$.

\i This flattening of a Pythagorean third is accomplished by
flattening the fifths by one-quarter of the syntonic comma.
This is called a {\em diminished fifth} and has a frequency
ratio:
%
\be
\frac{3}{2}\delta^{-1/4} = 
\frac{3}{2}\left(\frac{81}{80}\right)^{-1/4}
= 1.4953
\ee
%

\i Using a diminished fifth in place of a just fifth,
the construction of the mean-tone chromatic scale
is identical to that for the Pythagorean chromatic scale,
as shown in Figure~\ref{f:mean-chromatic-scale}.
%
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{mean-chromatic-scale}
