\i The major thirds (C to E, F to A, and G to B) 
have been flattened by the syntonic comma $\delta$ so that
they now have the just frequency ratio of 5:4.

\i All the major seconds (i.e., whole tone intervals
C to D, D to E, F to G, etc.)
have been flattened by $\delta/2$ so they now have a
frequency ratio of $\sqrt{5}:2 = 1.118$, instead of
$9:8 = 1.1250$ in Pythagorean temperament.

\i If one goes all away around the circle of fifths
using diminished fifths, one finds that the circle
doesn't close by $-41$~cents.
(In other words, 12 diminished fifths is short of 
7 octaves by an interval of 41 cents.)

\i For comparison, for Pythagorean temperament, 
the circle of fifths also doesn't close, 
overshooting by $23$~cents.

\i Similar to Pythagorean temperament, the fifth
from C$^\sharp$ to A$^\flat$ is out of tune.
It differs from a perfect fifth by 36~cents,
which is more than the difference for Pythagorean
tuning, which was $-23$~cents.
 
