\i \demo
Use the matlab routine fifths.m to compare the two
different fifths, C to G and C$^\sharp$ to A$^\flat$,
in the four different tuning systems that we considered.

\i There is no perfect tuning system.
Each system makes some compromise:

i) Equal temperament: Music in equal temperament 
can be played equally-well in all keys at the expense of 
imperfect intervals in all keys---e.g., a perfect 
fifth doesn't have a frequency
ratio of 3/2, a major third doesn't have a frequency
ratio of 5/4, etc.
The circle of fifths closes.

ii) Pythagorean tuning has just perfect fifths
in the key of C, but major thirds that 
are sharper than just major thirds by the 
syntonic comma $\delta = 1.0125$ (22 cents)
even in the key of C.
This means that major chords like 
C-E-G sound out of tune.
Also, even perfect fifths are no longer 
just perfect fifths when one moves away from the 
key of C---e.g., the wolf fifth 
C$^\sharp$ to A$^\flat$ is 23 cents too flat.

iii) Mean-tone tuning modifies Pythagorean tuning
so that it has just major thirds (ratio 5/4) 
in the key of C, at the expense of having 
perfect fifths that are a quarter-comma (5 cents)
too flat.
So the major chords like C-E-G sound better in
mean-tone tuning than in Pythagorean tuning, 
at least in the key of C.
But as before, things get worse as one moves 
away from the key of C---e.g., the perfect fifth
C$^\sharp$ to A$^\flat$ is now 36 cents too sharp.

iv) Just temperament is the ideal tuning system
in the key of C having perfect fifths and major
thirds with frequency ratios of 3/2 and 5/4, 
respectively.
But just like Pythagorean and mean-tone tuning,
just temperament gets progressively worse as one 
moves away from the key of C---e.g., the perfect
fifth C$^\sharp$ to A$^\flat$ is now 41 cents too sharp.

\ei

